TI  - Robust adaptive model-free depth tracking control of under-actuated LAUV with experimental results
PY  - 2024
JO  - OCEAN ENGINEERING
DO  - 10.1016/j.oceaneng.2024.117989
AB  - In this study a robust adaptive model-free depth tracking control scheme for the under-actuated lightweight autonomous underwater vehicle (LAUV) with guidance compensation and disturbance rejection, is presented. The proposed scheme includes a double-layer architecture including a kinematic guidance layer and a dynamic control layer. On the kinematic layer, the adaptive line-of-sight guidance with angle of attack compensation is employed to convert depth error into pitch error to address the under-actuated control issue. Additionally, a tracking differentiator is implemented to adjust the desired input parameters and to improve transient performance. On the kinetic layer, an improved model-free adaptive tracking algorithm based on I/O datadriven approaches is provided. The mathematical model is replaced by an approximate data model derived through dynamic linearization. In the proposed tracking scheme, an extended state observer in discrete time form is also incorporated to predict and compensate higher-order unmodeled dynamics and external disturbances. The proposed scheme has been validated through experimental results obtained from LAUV underwater maneuvering tests conducted in a towing tank. These results validate the algorithm's superiority and efficacy in achieving depth tracking control of LAUV, particularly in less accurate, complex and challenging modeling scenarios.
