TI  - Finite-time coordinated path following control of underactuated surface vehicles based on event-triggered mechanism
PY  - 2022
JO  - OCEAN ENGINEERING
DO  - 10.1016/j.oceaneng.2022.110530
AB  - This paper investigates the finite-time coordinated path following (CPF) control of underactuated surface vehicles (USVs) based on event-triggered mechanism. Initially, an event-triggered extended state observer (ET-FTESO) is designed, which can not only estimate the compound disturbances and the unmeasured velocities simultaneously in finite time, but also reduce the sensor-to-observer communication cost. Furthermore, a finite -time line-of-sight (FTLOS) guidance law is proposed for each USV to track the reference path. Then, under the condition of one-way communication, the coordinated update law of path variable is designed so that all USVs keep the same distance from each other along one curve. Specifically, finite-time CPF controllers via fast terminal sliding mode control (FTSMC) technique are proposed for each USV. On this basis, by combining with the relative threshold event-triggered mechanism, the controllers will be updated if and only if event-triggered conditions are satisfied. Therefore, it can greatly reduce the update rate of controller and mechanical loss of actuator. Subsequently, the stability analysis demonstrates that the closed-loop system is uniformly globally finite-time stable. And, it is proved by theory that the Zeno behavior can be avoided. Finally, numerical simulation results illustrate the effectiveness of the proposed control scheme.
